{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5202","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:37 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:37 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">The basic word order in Tibetan is Subject-Object-Verb. As is often the case in languages with this SOV word order, there are no prepositions but postpositions. This is part of a general tendency in Tibetan, in which the main information is deferred to the end of a clause or sentence. The head nouns of the relative clauses are usually placed after the relative clauses. Moreover, the main clause, which goes at the end of the statement, is always placed after the subordinate clauses (object, causal, etc.).<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Word order within a noun phrase is as follows:<\/p><ul> <li>Noun + [Adjective + Determinant + Plural Marker] + Case<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">Thus, the substantive comes first, followed by the qualifying adjective, the article (or demonstrative adjective), the plural marker, and the case. The case particle takes last place in the noun phrase (although it may happen that the case marker is followed by a topicalizer <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>). For example:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f99\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f97\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f7c\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo those pretty girls\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In Tibetan, then, there are no prepositions but only postpositions: the equivalents of \u201cin,\u201d \u201con,\u201d \u201cwith,\u201d and so on all follow the noun to which they relate. We don\u2019t say \u201cin the water\u201d but \u201cwater in\u201d; not \u201con the table\u201d but \u201ctable on.\u201d<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Postpositions are always followed by a case particle, usually the locative case (but also sometimes other cases such as the genitive or the ablative). They also command the genitive, which is inserted between the noun group and the postposition. The structure of the prepositional phrase is therefore:<\/p><ul> <li>Noun (or Noun Phrase) + [Genitive <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>] + Postposition + Locative <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">Note: While the genitive is always used when the preceding word ends in a vowel, its use is optional with certain postpositions when the preceding word ends in a consonant. This is particularly the case with: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cin,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f92\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201con,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cbehind,\u201d and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f51\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cin front of.\u201d<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Some examples of constructions using postpositions are:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0fb3\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the park\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b(\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b)\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the book\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f45\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f59\u0f7a\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cUnder the table\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f5b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb3\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the world\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fb3\u0f7c\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the lesson\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fb3\u0f7c\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0fad\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f41\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cNext to the school\u201d<\/li> <\/ul>","title":""}]}
